ce:section.ce:para:
Environmental issues have led to a big push into renewable energy sources and, consequently, energy storage facilities. Major initiatives are being planned or underway to enhance the implementation of regulation for minimizing the rate of climate change. As a result, the role of renewable energy sources among global energy sources is multiplying rapidly [1,2]. Preference for electric vehicles over combustion engine vehicles will also drive electric energy sources’ demand to unprecedented levels shortly [3]. Renewable energy sources are in abundance, but they suffer inefficiency, a considerable contributor to which is the energy storage mechanism deployed.Electric energy can be converted to chemical energy using active material in the most efficient and user-friendly manner [4]. Electrochemical energy storage devices can be categorized as fuel cells, supercapacitors, and batteries [5]. There are two basic types of batteries, main and secondary (rechargeable) batteries, with each battery cell consisting of an oxidizing agent (cathode) and a reducing agent (anode) separated by an electrolytethat transfers charge carriers between them [6]. Whereas secondary batteries are those for which this chemical reaction is reversible for at least a limited number of cycles on the application of external work.Here, we focus on secondary or rechargeable batteries. Rechargeable batteries’ cathode acts as host framework, allowing entry and exit of mobile charge carriers over a solid-solution range, which further defines its capacity [6]. In 1859, the French physician Gaston Planté invented the first rechargeable battery, the Lead-acid battery; then, many new electrode materials have been used for batteries [7]. Mizushimaet al.,pioneering research work, established that transition-metal lithium oxides LiMO2 crystallizing in layered structure could serve as cathodes with larger negative free energy change for each reaction [8]. In 1996, Padhi et al. proposed LiFePO4as a new cathode material for Li-ion batteries (LIB) [9]. LiFePO4 (LFP) serves as a positive electrode material. Itoffersgood structure stabilitybecause of its Phosphate olivine crystal structure, which allows Li-ions to diffuse in the 1D tunnel along with its b axis, as shown in Fig. 1
                     , [10]. Also, LFPbelongs to the olivine type compound and exhibiting high theoretical specific capacity (170 mAhg−1), higher energy density, excellent thermal and chemical stability, the high redox potential of Fe2+/Fe3+, safety, cost-effectiveness,environmental friendliness,and long cycle life. Hence, such unique characteristics have made LFP one of the most attractive cathode materials for the next generation rechargeable lithium-ion batteries (LIBs) [11–13]. Rechargeable LIBs have been anticipated as the most optimistic energy storage devices for not merely for portable electronics although too larger degree applications, for instance, energy storage systems for alternating renewable energy sources likethe wind as well as solar energy and also for electric-powered vehicles (EPVs) and plug-in hybrid electric vehicles (PHEV) owing tocharacteristics mentioned above of LEP. LiFePO4 and itsdelithiated phase FePO4 have a similar structure and only a slight difference in volume, which also causes capacity retention of LiFePO4 during charging and discharging [14]. Li+ intercalate reversibly into the cathode and anode of the Li-ion battery with the electrolyte acting as a conducting medium.The electrolyte may be solid or liquid;the solid electrolyte has gaseous or liquid electrodes as solid-solid surface interactions are complicated; therefore, liquid electrolytes are more suitable for solid electrodes. Electrolyte permits the diffusion of Li-ions between the cathode and anode, but it restricts the flow of electrons inside the cell so that they are pushed out to do external work [6]. The diffusivity of Li-ions in the electrolyte is much less than that of electrons in the metallic connectors at the anode/cathode of the cell, thus the surface area of the anode and cathode is kept large to allow conductivity of electrons through the external circuit to the redox centers of the Li-ion cell, (Fig. 2
                     ), [15]. The voltage of a Li-ion cell is also limited by the window of the electrolyte, which is the energy gap between the HOMO (highest occupied molecular orbital) and LUMO (lowest unoccupied molecular orbital) of the electrolyte, as shown in (Fig. 3
                     ) [6]. The current (I), for a time Δt, both also depends on the kinetics of the reaction at the interface of electrode and the electrolyte as well as the diffusion of ions in the electrolyte, the speed limitation of the Li-ions taking part in the chemical reaction at the electrode-electrolyte interface act as a resistance to the flow of current also called charge transfer resistance Rct 
                     [16] also a separation of charge occurring at the electrode-electrolyte interface act as a double-layered capacitor Cdl 
                     [17]. Thus, electrolyte greatly defines the performance of a LIB. Although, optimization of each component is important for increasing conversion efficiency, better performance, and cost reduction of battery. Here our focus is on the electrolyte; electrolyte should be chosen as such that it does not react with the cathode material irreversibly, and if possible, the electrochemical stability window (ESW) of the electrolyte medium must be more than the open-circuit voltage across the battery.The effects of KOH, Na2SO4, and NaOH in aqueous solution as electrolytes with LiFePO4 (LFP) as a cathode material synthesize using the hydrothermal way synthesis employing surfactant CTAB (Cetyltrimethylammonium Bromide) are discussed in this present work. Researchers have studied the electrochemical behavior of LFP cathodes under these electrolytes [18–20].

Electrochemical impedance spectroscopy (EIS) probe is useful in understanding the kinetics of the charge transfer reactions and mass-transfer limitations at the electrode-electrolyte interface [43,44], EIS complex plane plot for the different electrolyte systems is shown in Fig. 10
                            (a), with the frequency being varied in the range of 0.1 Hz–100KHz. In the high-frequency range, adepressingarc is observed in all three cases,which is attributed to the charge transfer process at the electrode-passivation layer surface and the passivation layer-solution interface, transfer of charge at these interfaces are controlled by the reaction kinetics and the mass-transfer limitations in the active electrode, passivation layer, and the electrolyte solution.The Faradic resistance due tothe redox reaction rate constant is called charge-transfer resistance, i.e., Rct. It is calculated from the approximate radius of the curve in the high-frequency region. Total current (i) for the LFP cell is a combination of the Faradic current (iF
                           ) and the discharge current (ic
                           ) through the double-layered capacitor (Cdl), as shown in the circuit in Fig. 10(b), where the Cdl behaves as a constant phase element (CPE) effectively due to roughness and heterogeneity of the surface. At very high frequency, current mostly flows through the Cdl and not via the Faradic impedance (ZF), and at high-frequency Cdl offers very little impedance. Therefore, the total impedance is roughly equal to the resistance provided by the solution (Rsol),which is estimated fromthe x-axis intercept of the complex plane plot [39]. Rsol is attributed to the electrolyte solution's resistivity and the spreading of current from the localized electrode to a distant counter electrode in the solution [40]. At low frequencies, the complex plane plot in Fig. 10(a) draws an inclined line, which is attributed to the mass-transfer limitations due to low diffusion of carrier ions in the solution, passivation layer and the active part of the electrode, the impedance offered as a result of the mass-transfer limitation is represented by Warburg impedance (W) as shown in Fig. 10(b).From Table 2
                           , it is clear that Rct and Rsol values for 2M NaOH and 1M KOH are approximately the same. The limiting value of the impedance as frequency tends to zero is an estimate of the cell's polarization resistance, polarization resistance is the ratio of the change in the potential to the change in current when it is varied very slowly. Fig. 10(c) shows that at a very low-value of the given frequencies, the real part of impedance (ZRE) is tending tothe lowest value for 1M KOH electrolyte, which indicates that the LFP electrode with 1M KOH as electrolyte has the lowest polarization resistance.
